-{"id":"flywheel_connectors-u1q92","title":"[REVIEW][MEDIUM] fcp-e2e/*: shadow host_allowed helper diverges from production host_matches_allow_list (conformance harness drift risk)","description":"All 84 crates/fcp-e2e/tests/*_compliance_e2e.rs suites define a local "fn host_allowed(host, host_allow) -> bool" that shadows the real production matcher at crates/fcp-sandbox/src/egress.rs:638 EgressGuard::host_matches_allow_list. The shadow and production disagree on three edge cases: (1) bare "*" wildcard — production treats "*" as allow-all, shadow compares literally and rejects; (2) empty-subdomain against "*.example.com" — production enforces host.len() > suffix.len() so ".example.com" fails, shadow only does host.ends_with(".example.com") and accepts; (3) shadow skips canonicalize_host_pattern, so any future pattern shape the canonicalizer normalizes (e.g. uppercase) will match differently. Today every manifest-level host_allow in the 84 suites uses exact hostnames (no wildcards), so no test currently fails — but the shadow is a drift trap: a connector adopting a wildcard host_allow would pass the shadow assertion while the production egress guard rejects (or vice versa), and a future production tightening of the wildcard rules would not surface in CI. Suggested fix: either expose fcp_sandbox::EgressGuard::host_matches_allow_list via a pub(crate) test helper or pub testkit function, or drive the host-allow check by constructing NetworkConstraints + EgressRequest and calling the pub EgressGuard::evaluate() path. Either removes the shadow and makes the compliance test track the real enforcement. File: crates/fcp-e2e/tests/bitbucket_compliance_e2e.rs:394-401 is the canonical shape — identical helpers in all 84 suites. Reviewer: cc_2.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T18:23:53.728745Z","created_by":"jemanuel","updated_at":"2026-04-24T18:23:53.728745Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
